The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, July 02, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, July 1: The government today said that a concept paper for reviewing the Companies Act would be released on July 31, paving the way to pruning of two-third of the provisions of the complex law. The concept paper will be released to simplify the act to bring in more transparency and ensure investors protection. Two-third of the provisions of the act is redundant and has no relevance whatsoever, minister of state for company affairs Prem Chand Gupta said. Once the paper was released, the government would invite suggestions from industry chambers and national bodies of chartered accountants and company secretaries.																								 Mumbai, July 1: The Bombay High Court today upheld Maharashtra Electricity Regulatory Authoritys order and asked Tata Power to pay Rs 289 crore to MSEB towards standby charges within seven months in three instalments.																								 New Delhi, July 1: Escorts Ltd has offloaded its entire 78 per cent stake in Escorts Auto Components (EACL) in favour of EACL chief Bharat Caprihan and a few other senior executives. Meanwhile, Escorts has posted a net loss of Rs 193.1 crore for the quarter ended March 31, 2004 against a net profit of Rs 67.8 crore a year earlier.																								 Calcutta, July 1: India Foils Ltd, a Sterlite group firm, plans to set up a 3.6 MW power-plant at its Kamarhati unit in Bengal.																								 New Delhi, July 1: Gail India has declared a total dividend of 80 per cent for 2003-04. It includes the 40 per cent interim dividend paid earlier.
